etymologies: mid 19th century; earliest use found in Chemical News. From ace- + naphthene, after French acénaphtène

definitions: A crystalline aromatic hydrocarbon found in coal tar and used in the manufacture of dyes and pesticides.

notes.text: Acenaphthene has a tricyclic molecule similar to that of acenaphthylene except that the ethylene bridging group is saturated. Systematic name: 1,2-dihydroacenaphthylene; C₁₂H₁₀.
